[9] <a href="javascript:card_browser(243)">Tol Brandir</a><br>
<br>
Free Peoples<br>
 Gandalf, The Grey Pilgrim (starting)<br>
 <a href="javascript:card_browser(193)">Sam, Son of Hamfast</a><br>
 <a href="javascript:card_browser(245)">Aragorn, King in Exile</a>  x3<br>
 <a href="javascript:card_browser(306)">Boromir, Lord of Gondor</a>  x3<br>
 <a href="javascript:card_browser(250)">Elrond, Lord of Rivendell</a>  x2<br>
 Barliman Butterbur<br>
 Filbert Bolger<br>
 <a href="javascript:card_browser(303)">Armor</a>  x2<br>
 <a href="javascript:card_browser(937)">Flaming Brand</a>  x2<br>
 <a href="javascript:card_browser(11)">Ranger&#39;s Sword</a><br>
 <a href="javascript:card_browser(305)">Blade of Gondor</a><br>
 <a href="javascript:card_browser(284)">Glamdring</a>  x2<br>
 <a href="javascript:card_browser(927)">Gandalf&#39;s Staff</a><br>
 Narya<br>
 <a href="javascript:card_browser(194)">Sting</a>  x3<br>
 <a href="javascript:card_browser(293)">Servant of the Secret Fire</a>  x4<br>
 <a href="javascript:card_browser(294)">Sleep, Caradhras</a>  x2<br>
 Fireworks<br>
<br>
Shadow<br>
 <a href="javascript:card_browser(994)">Orc Scout</a>ing Band  x4<br>
 <a href="javascript:card_browser(319)">Orc Ambusher</a>  x4<br>
 <a href="javascript:card_browser(994)">Orc Scout</a>  x4<br>
 <a href="javascript:card_browser(149)">Orc Assassin</a>  x4<br>
 <a href="javascript:card_browser(998)">Tower Assassin</a>  x2<br>
 <a href="javascript:card_browser(125)">Ulaire Enquea, Lieutenant of Morgul</a> x2<br>
 <a href="javascript:card_browser(150)">Orc Bowmen</a>  x4<br>
 <a href="javascript:card_browser(321)">Under the Watching Eye</a>  x4<br>
 <a href="javascript:card_browser(140)">Hate</a>  x2<br>
 <a href="javascript:card_browser(867)">Enduring Evil</a>  x2    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> Long Strategy read all or don&#39;t review!!!<br>
<br>
If you are wondering and even if you are not, the title is from the Jimmy Buffett song Miss You So Badly.  Also if anyone knows what the Gong Show is, please D-mail me.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
This deck is the latest version of my many GandalfSauron decks.  I have played this deck since my second tournament way back in December &#39;01.  I have always liked it and in my meta Sauron is not popular so I always manage to take at least 2 opponents by surprise every tournament.  Uruk Hai and Nazgul are the biggies in my meta.  There is some moria mixed in though.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Free Peoples<br>
<br>
 My favorite card of all time is most definetly Sting.  It took me up until a month ago to finally get 3.  After reading the excellant article "Mind Tricks: The Power of Compulsion" I realized just how good Sting is.  Using Sting once a turn makes it so there is no way your opponent can bluff your fellowship and somewhat less effectively your shadow.  I use three so I can get it pronto.  I use it every fellowship phase and depending on my memory some regroup phases.  The most important thing though is to look at every card in your opponent&#39;s hand and read any you don&#39;t know the text to.  The biggest mistake people make with Sting is mainly they only look at shadow and depending on the playeropponent just the number of orcs they have.  But make sure you always look at the whole hand Free Peoples, Shadow, weapons, events etc.  On a side note, in multiplayer games anytime someone uses Sting make sure the Stung player shows his hand to everyone.<br>
<br>
 Anyways, with that explained we can go on to how to play this deck.  The reason I did this version of Gandalf and not the Trust Me version is simple I like to be able to Sleep whenever I want to and the only RotEL I have came from the prerelease event I went to.  I generally bid 5-6 but depending on the opponent I bid as much as 8.  I try to move 1-3; 3-4,5(depending on whats in oppnents hand); 4 or 5 to 6(depending on wether you moved to 5 last turn); 6-8;8-9.  This doesn&#39;t always happen but ideally this is what I shoot for.  At the first couple sites you are giving up alot of twilight so use Sting or Glamdring to see what you can afford to put out.  With a combined 5 Stings and Glamdrings you should be able to look at your opponents hand on the first turn and as explained above I highly recommend doing so.  Pull Sam, play what you can play safely from hand and move on.  Servants do not have to be used sparingly being as you have a possible 8 with Fireworks and Barliman.  Another pet peave of mine is deck ciculation.  In almost all of my decks I have an effective way to draw extra cards routinely.  Obviously in this deck I have Gandalf and the two Elronds.  Depending on what I am playing against Elrond does not always come down.  For example I might not want to give a Moria deck an Elf to spot with the Scout.  Again with looking at your opponents hand each turn you should be able to determine how many times Elrond can be safely used a turn.  Lookout for the Tower Assassin and Power is in Terror mainly.  Sleep gets rid of conditions and with fireworks and Barliman have no quams about ditching it to clean out your hand early on.  That about wraps it up for the Free Peoples side.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Shadow<br>
<br>
 This is your basic direct damage Sauron deck.  I have been playing it forever it seems like.  Over the past months I have realized this deck requires a certain amount of effeincy in deck circulation in order to cause the most damage possible in the quickest amount of time.  At first I tried using only 8 trackers this didn&#39;t couple to well becuase I never had a tracker and an UTWE at the same time.  So I moved up to 16.  Excessive yes I believe 12 would work just fine.  However I decided about a month and a haleasterlingo that with the fact that every fellowship would Map out Tol Brandir a sort of Sauron swarm was capable.  You could easily get out between 7-8 minions.  So I decided to go with all the cheap ones.  And early on this allows me to get my hand cycled faster seeing as I could routinely play 2-3 guys through the first five sites.  As mentioned in the Free Peoples strategy circulation is important.  I must get my UTWE and Bowmen out early and a relatively small deck (64 cards) coupled with fellowship drawing techniques and shadow side minion circulation allows this rather effectively.  The first thing that comes to mind when some hears Sauron Condition deck is "Hmmm? thats easy to beat all you need is condition removal."  And true a well timed Sleep can put a cramp in my plans.  However it is almost never crippling.  Mainly becuase I only need 3 conditions out to deliver a painful amount of damage to the opponent.  Rarely do I have more than 4 so unless you use 3 Sleeps or draw the ones you use at exactly the right time I can continuosly cause damage.  Yes it hurts but it is not game ending.  As mentioned above if all else fails you can try for the swarm at site 9.  It is possible to get between 5 and 9 minions out.  A note on Sleep Carahdras is that with most Gandalf decks being Trust Me As you Once Did most are not playing more than one Sleep for fear of canceling their own condition.  A side effect of all the direct damage is that people tend late game to pile burdens on in order to keep their companions alive.  For this reason I added the surprise aspect of 2 Enduring Evils and 2 Enqueas.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Card Choices<br>
<br>
 [Sting] 3 so I can draw it.  Explained in detail in the first paragraph.<br>
<br>
 [Filbert] Hurts the site nine Uruk fierce saruman or site.  Extremely effective against the Naz and the Twi Naz.  Balrog and Cavetroll too.<br>
<br>
 [Barliman]  Never know when you might need that one extra Gandalf card.<br>
<br>
 [Fireworks]  Same as Barliman.<br>
<br>
 [Aragorn KIE]  Uruks are quite popular in my meta so the extra healing ability is well liked.  Allows me to heal Frodo every turn so that I can use Sting.  Usually don&#39;t need the swarm protection of ROTN.<br>
<br>
 [Hate]  For some reason people seem to think in order for Hate to be effective you need 4.  In my deck that is not so.  I use a hate any chance I have to kill a companion.  Killing Sam as soon as he removes 3 burdens is always fun.  Plus companions are almost always going to be exhausted late game.  And if you want you can save one to kill Aragorn at the last site after he has exerted to take on 3 people.  The main thing is to use hate when it is convenient.  Not to mention it is against the idea of my deck to save card in my hand and most of my guys can only exert once anyways.<br>
<br>
 [Enduring Evil]  People start putting burdens on for archery so why not.  At site 9 when Frodo is fighting an ambusher play this and kill him.<br>
<br>
 [Enquea]  People would sometimes rather put burdens on for archery.  And for those pesky nine companion decks that give all the exertions and wounds to the speedbumps.<br>
<br>
<br>
Site Choice<br>
 [Green Dragon Inn]  Pulls Sam denies the Pony and lets me go first<br>
 {Breeland Forest]  I don&#39;t use stealth events so why not never know when it is going to come in handy.<br>
 [Rivendell Terrace]  I like drawing and I use 3 extra men<br>
 [Eregion Hills]  Doesn&#39;t hurt fellowship and helps Enduring Evil and Enquea<br>
 [Bridge]  Pulls the Balrog is that awesome.  Wait&#39; I don&#39;t use the Balrog. "hmmm?  Decisions Decisions"<br>
 [Glade]  Neutral Doesn&#39;t hurt or help Free or Shadow<br>
 [Silverlode Banks]  I like exertions.<br>
 [Shores]  9 pool and play 5 orcs to stop them<br>
 [Tol Brandir]  Pulls people from dead pile.<br>
<br>
<br>
That is about all.  Constructive critism is wanted.  Any questions D-mail me or IM me at buffett2005.<br>
